dataIdInfo.idPurp: To produce the tsunami warning products, the a Decision Support Tool (Tsunami) relies on the geographical definitions of the Tsunami Warning Zones (TWZs) and key coastal places in each zone.
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
The Joint Australian Tsunami Warning Centre (JATWC) uses a Decision Support Tool (DST) to assess tsunami threat, and to prepare and disseminate tsunami warnings. To produce the tsunami warning products, the DST relies on the geographical definitions of the Tsunami Warning Zones (TWZs) and key coastal places in each zone.

The TWZ zones are essentially the same as the Coastal Waters Forecast Zones (CWFZs) except where inshore bays and waters are too refined for tsunami warning purposes. For example, the bays adjacent to the Southeast Coast of Tasmania are treated as the extension of the Southeast Coast. The TWZ zones are normally updated whenever there are major changes to the CWFZ zones such as the recent (date ?) Queensland changes to include an additional Torres Strait coastal water zone.

The key coastal places identified in each TWZ zone fall into two broad categories. They are:

1. A list of Significant Locations. These coastal places are used by the Tsunami Travel Time (TTT) software to produce the estimated tsunami arrival times (ETAs). The ETA times at those places under the threat zones will be provided in the warning bulletins. It is worth noting that TTT also produces ETA times at sea level observation stations for verification purposes.

2. A list of Priority Towns. These coastal places are used in the Community Response Advice for evacuation when under Land Threat. They are usually the more populated towns/villages in each zone.

Date, July 2014
